Superstore Sales: Exploratory Data Analysis

1. Project Goal

The objective of this project is to conduct a comprehensive Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) on the Superstore dataset. Aiming to uncover key insights related to sales performance, customer behavior, and profitability across different regions, product categories, and segments. The findings will help identify opportunities for growth and areas for operational improvement.

2. The Dataset

This analysis uses the classic "Superstore" dataset, a popular resource for demonstrating data analysis and visualization skills. The dataset contains detailed information on orders, products, customers, and sales.

  • Source: Kaggle Superstore Dataset

Data Dictionary

This dictionary provides a description for each column in the dataset.

Order Information

  • Row ID: Unique identifier for each row.
  • Order ID: Identifier for each distinct order.
  • Order Date: The date the order was placed.
  • Ship Date: The date the order was shipped.
  • Ship Mode: The shipping method for the order (e.g., 'Standard Class').

Customer & Location Information

  • Customer ID: Unique identifier for each customer.
  • Customer Name: The name of the customer.
  • Segment: The customer segment (e.g., 'Consumer', 'Corporate').
  • Country: The country of the order (Note: All are 'United States').
  • City: The city of the order.
  • State: The state of the order.
  • Postal Code: The postal code of the location.
  • Region: The region of the country (e.g., 'South', 'West').

Product Information

  • Product ID: Unique identifier for each product.
  • Category: The main product category (e.g., 'Furniture', 'Office Supplies').
  • Sub-Category: The specific product sub-category (e.g., 'Chairs', 'Paper').
  • Product Name: The name of the product.

Financial Information

  • Sales: The total sale amount for the transaction (numeric).
  • Quantity: The number of units sold (numeric).
  • Discount: The discount applied to the sale (numeric, percentage in decimal form).
  • Profit: The profit generated from the sale (numeric).

Initial observations

  1. 1 Critical Issue: The Dates are Strings (object).

    The Clue: df.info() shows Order Date and Ship Date have Dtype: object. We cannot perform any time-series analysis (e.g., "What were our monthly sales?," "How long does shipping take?") until these are converted to proper datetime objects. This is our highest priority cleaning task.

  2. Data Granularity and Structure Looking at the unique counts. Row ID is unique (9994), but Order ID is not (5009). The head() shows two rows with the same Order ID (CA-2016-152156). This tells us the granularity of the data is at the product-in-an-order level. Each row is not one order; it is one product line item within an order. An order can contain multiple products, hence multiple rows with the same Order ID. This is a crucial understanding for how we will aggregate our data later.

  3. Data Cleaning and Formatting (Column Names) The column names have spaces and mixed case (e.g., Row ID, Order Date, Product Name). This is inconvenient for coding. Accessing columns with df.Row ID won't work due to the space. It's best practice to standardize column names to a consistent format.This makes the code much cleaner and less error-prone.

  4. Interesting Numerical Distributions Looking at the describe() output for Profit. The Insight: The min value for profit is -6599.97. This is a massive loss on a single transaction! The max is also very high. The std (standard deviation) is huge (234), while the mean is small (28). This tells us that the Profit column is heavily skewed and has extreme outliers. We will definitely need to investigate these high-loss and high-profit orders. The same applies to Sales.

  5. Redundant or Useless Columns Country has only 1 unique value ('United States'). A column where every value is the same provides no information. We can safely drop this. Row ID is also just an index and can likely be dropped. Customer Name is redundant if we have Customer ID.

A Note on Data Granularity

A crucial first step in understanding this dataset is to recognize its granularity. By observing the Row ID and Order ID columns from our initial report, we can see:

  • Each row has a unique Row ID.
  • Multiple rows can share the same Order ID.

This means that each row in the dataset does not represent a unique customer order. Instead, each row represents a single product line item within a larger order.

For example, a single customer order (Order ID: 'ABC-123') consisting of a chair and a table would appear as two separate rows in this dataset, both sharing the 'ABC-123' identifier.

Implication for Analysis: This understanding is critical. When we analyze metrics like sales and profit, we are looking at the performance of individual product lines. To analyze the total value of an entire customer order, we will need to aggregate the data by grouping it by order_id. This structure also explains the presence of extreme outliers in sales and profit, as they often correspond to single, high-value (or high-discount) items within a larger basket of products.

2. Data Cleaning and Preparation

The initial report reveals several areas that require cleaning and preprocessing before we can begin our analysis. Our prioritized action plan is as follows:

  1. Standardize Column Names: Convert all column names to a consistent snake_case format for easier coding.
  2. Convert Date Columns: Change Order Date and Ship Date from object to datetime objects to enable time-series analysis.
  3. Drop Redundant Columns: Remove columns that provide no analytical value, such as Row ID and Country.
  4. Check for Missing Values and Duplicates: Although the initial report shows none, we will perform a final check after our transformations.

2.1 Standardize Column Names

The current column names contain spaces and mixed casing (e.g., Order ID, Sub-Category), which can be cumbersome for coding. We will convert them all to a standard snake_case format (e.g., order_id, sub_category) for consistency and ease of use. A list comprehension provides a clean and efficient way to do this for all columns at once.

Cleaned Column Names:
Index(['row_id', 'order_id', 'order_date', 'ship_date', 'ship_mode',

      dtype='object')

Pandas provides a powerful, built-in function pd.to_datetime() that can intelligently parse most common date formats. We will apply this to both date columns.

3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

With a fully cleaned and prepared dataset, we can now dive into the exploration phase. Our analysis will be structured around four key business questions (what, which, where, when):

  1. Sales & Profit Performance: What are our overall sales and profit numbers? What do their distributions look like?
  2. Product Analysis: Which product categories and sub-categories are the most and least profitable?
  3. Temporal Analysis: How do sales and profit change over time? Are there identifiable trends or seasonal patterns?
  4. Geographical Analysis: Which regions, states, and cities are our top markets?

Let's begin by analyzing the overall performance metrics.

3.1 Sales and Profit Analysis

The most fundamental metrics for any retail business are sales and profit. Let's start by examining the distribution of these two key numerical features. We've already seen from our initial report that they have a wide range and potential outliers, so visualizing their distributions is crucial.

--- Descriptive Statistics for Sales and Profit ---
              sales       profit

50%       54.480000     8.671000
75%      209.940000    29.364000
max    22638.480000  8399.976000

Observations:

  • Heavily Skewed Distributions: Both sales and profit are heavily right-skewed. The vast majority of transactions are small-value sales that generate a small profit. The mean is pulled to the right by a small number of very large transactions.
  • Significant Losses: The profit distribution shows a substantial number of transactions result in a loss (values less than 0). The minimum profit is a staggering loss of over $6,500. This is a major red flag that needs further investigation.

Insight: The business is a "game of singles," driven by a high volume of low-value transactions. However, there are significant outlier events (both huge wins and huge losses) that heavily influence the overall profit. A key analytical goal will be to identify what causes these extreme outcomes.

3.2 Product Category and Sub-Category Analysis

Now that we understand the overall sales and profit landscape, let's identify which product categories and sub-categories are the most significant contributors to the business. We will analyze this from two angles:

  1. Total Contribution: Which categories generate the most total sales and profit?
  2. Profitability: Which categories have the best profit margins and distributions?

Total Sales and Profit by Category

Observation (Category Level):

  • Technology is the clear leader in both sales and profit, generating the most revenue and the highest total profit.
  • Office Supplies generates a moderate amount of sales and a healthy profit.
  • Furniture is a major problem area. Despite generating the second-highest sales, it produces by far the lowest total profit. The profit is barely positive, indicating that this category is either operating on razor-thin margins or is incurring significant losses on some products.

Insight: The Furniture category requires immediate investigation. Why are high sales not translating into profit? This leads us perfectly into a deeper dive at the sub-category level.

Profitability Analysis: A Deep Dive into Sub-Categories

The aggregate data shows that Furniture is a problem category. To understand why, we need to analyze the distribution of profit for each sub_category. A box plot is the perfect tool to see which specific products are driving down the profitability of the entire category.

The box plot provides a detailed view of the profit distribution for each sub-category, confirming that Tables and Bookcases are consistently unprofitable. However, to understand the total impact on the business, we need to consider both the average profitability and the total sales volume.

Let's create a summary table that shows the sum of sales and profit alongside the mean profit for each sub-category. This will help us see how small, consistent losses can add up.

Final Insight on Product Performance:

The detailed summary table provides the definitive answer. The Furniture category is unprofitable primarily due to two sub-categories:

  • Tables: This is the biggest problem. High sales volume combined with a consistently negative average profit (driven by high average discounts) results in a massive total loss for the company.
  • Bookcases: A similar but smaller-scale issue of unprofitability.

Conversely, the most profitable sub-categories are Copiers and Phones, which combine high sales with high average profit margins. This analysis pinpoints exactly where the business should focus its efforts: re-evaluating the pricing and discount strategy for the Tables sub-category is a top priority.

3.3 Temporal Analysis: Sales and Profit Over Time

Now that we understand what we sell, let's analyze when we sell it. By analyzing sales and profit trends over time, we can identify growth patterns, seasonality, and other time-based insights that are crucial for forecasting, inventory management, and marketing campaigns.

Our first step is to aggregate our transactional data into a monthly time series.

--- First 5 Months of Aggregated Performance ---
                sales     profit
order_date                      
2014-01-31  14236.895  2450.1907
2014-02-28   4519.892   862.3084
2014-03-31  55691.009   498.7299
2014-04-30  28013.973  3500.8940
2014-05-31  23648.287  2738.7096

Observations from the Time Series Plot:

  • Clear Upward Trend: There is a distinct and positive trend in both sales and profit over the four-year period. The business is growing, with sales in later years consistently higher than in earlier years.
  • Strong Seasonality: A clear seasonal pattern emerges. Sales and profit consistently spike in the last quarter of each year (October, November, December), likely corresponding to holiday shopping and end-of-year business purchases. There is often a corresponding dip in the first quarter (January, February).
  • Profit Volatility: While sales are relatively smooth on their upward trend, profit is much more volatile. There are several months where profit dips sharply, even when sales remain high. This reinforces our earlier finding that certain transactions (likely those with high discounts) can severely impact profitability.

Insight and Business Value:

  • Forecasting: The clear trend and seasonality mean that future sales are highly predictable. The business can use this for inventory planning, ensuring they are well-stocked for the Q4 rush.
  • Marketing: Marketing campaigns can be timed to coincide with or boost the natural seasonal peaks. For example, a "Back to Business" sale in September could lead into the Q4 spike.
  • Performance Management: The company can set realistic, seasonally-adjusted targets. A sales dip in February is normal and not a cause for panic, whereas a dip in November would be a major red flag.

3.4 Geographical Analysis: Performance by Location

The final pillar of our EDA is to understand where our business thrives and where it struggles. By analyzing sales and profit across different regions, states, and cities, we can identify key markets, uncover regional performance issues, and inform decisions related to marketing, logistics, and expansion.

As you noted, the key business questions this analysis can answer are:

  • Which regions are our most profitable strongholds?
  • Are there underperforming states that need attention?
  • Can we identify specific cities that are either cash cows or major loss centers?
  • Where should we focus targeted advertising campaigns or logistical optimizations?

We'll start at the highest level: Region.

State-Level Performance

The regional analysis provides a good overview, but state-level performance is more actionable. Let's identify our top 10 most profitable and bottom 10 least profitable states. This will highlight where our strategy is working and where it's failing.

City-Level Deep Dive

The state-level analysis reveals several states with significant losses, such as Texas, Ohio, and Pennsylvania. To understand the root cause, we can drill down to the city level to see if specific metropolitan areas are responsible for these losses.

Geographical Insights:

  • Key Markets: California and New York are the undisputed titans, driving a massive portion of both sales and profit. Washington, Michigan, and Virginia are also very strong performers.
  • Problem States: The analysis clearly pinpoints several statesTexas, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Illinois, North Carolina, and Floridaas major sources of unprofitability. These states generate sales but result in an overall loss for the company.
  • Root Cause at City Level: The city-level analysis shows that the losses in these states are not evenly distributed. They are concentrated in major metropolitan areas like Philadelphia, Houston, San Antonio, Chicago, etc.

Actionable Recommendations: The company must conduct an urgent strategic review of its operations in the identified problem states and cities. This could involve re-evaluating local pricing, discount strategies, shipping costs, or competitor presence in these specific markets. Conversely, the successful strategies in California and New York could be studied and potentially replicated in other regions.

Observation

The Source of the Loss is One Order: The three most unprofitable line items all share the same order_id: CA-2016-108196, placed on November 25, 2016. This wasn't a series of bad experiences; it was one single, catastrophic shopping trip.

The "Cubify CubeX 3D Printer" is the Culprit: The single line item for this 3D printer resulted in a staggering loss of -$6,599.98. This one item is responsible for virtually the entire loss associated with this customer.

The Reason is the Discount: The discount applied to that printer was 70% (0.7). This is an astronomically high discount for a high-ticket technology item. The business sold five units of a ~3000 printer for about 900 each, leading to a massive loss. The same 70% discount was applied to the Binders in the same order, also causing a significant loss.

The Geographic Connection: This disastrous order was shipped to Lancaster, Ohio. This connects directly to our earlier geographical analysis, where we saw that Ohio was one of the most unprofitable states. This transaction is a major contributor to Ohio's poor performance.

Normal Customer Behavior Otherwise: Outside of this one order, the customer's other purchases were normal, profitable transactions for standard office supplies in California and Georgia, with reasonable or zero discounts. This shows that the problem isn't the customer per se, but the specific conditions of that one high-loss order.

Final Insight from Customer Drill-Down:

The customer-level analysis provides the most specific and actionable insight of this entire EDA. By drilling down into the single most unprofitable customer, CS-12505, we discovered that the -$6,626 loss was not due to a pattern of behavior, but to a single order (CA-2016-108196).

Within this order, a 70% discount was applied to a high-ticket technology item (a 3D printer), resulting in a loss of over $6,500 on that item alone. This transaction occurred in Ohio, one of the most unprofitable states identified earlier.

This is the root cause. The company's overall unprofitability is not just a general trend; it is heavily impacted by specific instances of an aggressive or perhaps flawed discounting strategy on high-value items in certain geographical regions.

Actionable Recommendation: The #1 recommendation from this analysis is for management to conduct an urgent review of the discount authorization policy.

  • Who is authorized to give a 70% discount?
  • What is the maximum allowable discount for products in the Technology category, especially in states that are already unprofitable?
  • Implementing stricter controls on high-value discounts could prevent these catastrophic losses and dramatically improve the company's bottom line.

4. Executive Summary & Strategic Recommendations

This comprehensive Exploratory Data Analysis of the Superstore dataset has yielded critical insights into the company's operational performance. By analyzing sales, profit, product, temporal, geographical, and customer data, we have identified key areas of strength to leverage and significant problems to address.

Key Findings at a Glance:

  • Overall Health: The business is on a clear growth trajectory, with sales increasing year-over-year. However, profitability is highly volatile and significantly hampered by specific, identifiable issues.
  • Product Performance: Technology is the most profitable category, driven by high-margin products like Copiers and Phones. The Furniture category is a major problem area, generating high sales but minimal profit due to massive losses in the Tables sub-category.
  • Temporal Patterns: The business is seasonal, with a significant sales and profit spike in Q4 of each year. This provides a predictable pattern for inventory and marketing planning.
  • Geographical Landscape: Performance is highly concentrated. California and New York are powerhouse states driving the majority of profit. Conversely, several large states, including Texas, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, are significant loss centers.

The Root Cause of Unprofitability:

The single most significant issue discovered is the company's discounting strategy on high-ticket items in unprofitable regions. Our drill-down analysis revealed that a single customer order for five 3D printers in Ohio, sold at a 70% discount, resulted in a loss of over $6,500. This one transaction highlights a systemic problem where aggressive discounts are destroying profit margins.

Top-Priority Strategic Recommendations:

  1. Urgent Discount Policy Review: Immediately implement stricter controls and approval processes for discounts exceeding a certain threshold (e.g., 25-30%), especially for high-cost technology items and within states that are already unprofitable.
  2. Re-evaluate the "Tables" Sub-Category: The Tables product line is a consistent loss leader. A full review of its pricing, sourcing costs, and discount strategy is required. The company should consider discontinuing unprofitable models if margins cannot be improved.
  3. Focus and Replicate Success: Double down on the successful strategies used in California and New York. Analyze the product mix and sales tactics in these regions to create a playbook that can be applied to mid-tier states.
  4. Implement a Customer VIP Program: Identify and assign account managers to the top 10-20 most profitable customers to ensure their retention, as they represent a disproportionately large share of the company's profit.

This data-driven analysis provides a clear roadmap for improving profitability and operational efficiency. The next step would be to develop targeted action plans based on these strategic recommendations.

Insights from the Interactive Map:

This interactive map provides a powerful, at-a-glance overview of the company's national performance and reinforces our earlier findings:

  • Bicoastal Powerhouses: The dark green colors immediately draw attention to the high-profit states on the coasts, primarily California and New York.
  • The "Problem Belt": A clear belt of red and orange (unprofitable) states is visible, running through Texas, Illinois, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and North Carolina.
